value.0: "We ready to go then?"
"Blast you to the furnace, you can't go out there alone. You will need my strength to face your enemies! Reconsider, friend."
"I am not used to followin', but I shall do my best."
"This is the kind of place where you order three drinks in the hopes that one won't have somethin' dead floatin' in it."
"Ack, now this is fun! Heaps of wee bonnie creatures to maim and mangle."
"What kind of a ragtag army is this? Pathetic!"
"Bet you could get loads of firewood out of that tree."
"There's got to be some good taverns in this keep. We should find them all!"
"This tavern has all the earmarks of quality. What do you say we spend a few days here and see if we can drink them dry!"
"I can feel the debauchery seepin' right out of me in this holy place. We need to leave here quickly!"
"Now this place probably serves fine wines, but the ladies will be a touch too refined for my tastes."
"Sort of makes you wonder if you made the right investment choices, now doesn't it?"
"Here goblin, goblin, goblin. Come out and play!"
"Now that is one attractive dwarf, if I might say so myself!"

Comment.value: in entrance to manticore cave, if on quest

value.0: "I don't understand why we cannae just slaughter the wee beasty and have done. What is a manticore, anyway?"
"Not many mages in these parts, but this one seems powerful enough."
"What I like about these kobolds is that they aren't singin'. Nothin' more irritatin' than a singin' kobold."
"We should walk out of the keep a ways and see if there are any enemy survivors to finish off."
"I don't know why the dwarves hate their cousins. They seem like an entertainin' lot."
"Walk softly now. This seems a dangerous place when the enemy is supposedly already dead."
"A very functional buildin', but we'll have to add a bar when we take over."
"A terribly cocky fellow. You'd think he'd have a few more guards than this."
"And how can Calibast be of assistance now?"
"Why? Do you like getting' your fool head knocked in by an enemy? Who's gonna watch your back, tell me that?"
"This had better mean you're comin' back soon. I'll be wantin' a drink, you can bet."
"Then I'm goin' for a drink at the Mossy Tree. I don't promise to be sober next time you need me though."
"Tactics are important. What do you want me to do?"
"A good idea. I don't really care for the old smash-through-the-trap routine anymore."
"Oh, sure, I'll just walk right over and use these stubby fingers to pretend I'm a nimble thief. Good thinkin', <sir/madam>."
"Great. With tactics like these, who needs enemies. You sure you want to be the leader here?"
"I'll do what I can, but I'm not sure what you're expectin'."
"Right. I'll try to contain my enthusiasm."
"Bash the livin' blazes out of doors and chests. Got it."
"Good. Tell me where to stand."
"I'll do what I can for you."
"Jump right in and beat them all down to size, eh? Right, that's my favorite tactic. I never get killed doin' that one."
"Right. Protect the <class>. I've played this game before."
"I'm pretty sure I can dress myself, but if you have suggestions... well, go ahead. Just don't be peekin' at anythin' you shouldn't!"
"I doubt I'll know much more than you would, but I'll give it a try."
"Seems like as good a time as any for a break. Could you pass the wine? Just kiddin'. No drinkin' on duty, I suppose."
"And how else can I help you now?"
"What? Is my head out? Hmm... nope. Seem to be fine, thanks."
"Anything else?"
"I grow weary of walkin'. Don't suppose you've learned to fly yet?"
"The smell of death is in the air. Let's go make a little for ourselves!"
"More killin', less talkin'!"
"I need a drink, next question?"
"Can't complain, nobody'd listen anyways!"
"I feel like a young wolf in a field of old deer. Pleasantly surprised and ready to give chase."
"Be fine if'n I could see a blasted thing!"
"I've been cut worse in many a tavern brawl. Don't be worryin' about me."
"I'm not keelin' over, if that's your worry."
"I could be doin' better. How about you?"
"Never could stand a fellow who used poison. Now I remember why."
"My stomach does nae feel so good. I only hope the flames on me head don't catch!"
Calibast chuckles. "I will stay around as long as you need and want me too. Azers have long lives, so eventually I will probably try to go home and see if things have changed."
"I would like a little revenge, but I'm in no rush. In the meantime, I hope you still want me around. This keep needs a few improvements."
"There are a couple of powerful rulers on my home plane. They took everythin' from me and someday I shall pay them back in kind."
"I have some plans, but that can wait for the future. Makin' the keep strong right now is far more important. My improvements should help."
Calibast shrugs, "I have some plans, but that can wait for the future. Makin' the keep strong right now is far more important. My improvements should help."
"I have a great deal of experience with defendin' and attackin' fortifications. For a start, some large, stake-filled pits around the walls and a barbican near the gates would help."
"If it is possible, I would like to divert some of the nearby river to fill a moat, which would help stop more miners from diggin under the walls."
"There are many different ways to make a castle more defendable. Some are more expensive, while some are quite easy and cheap."
"Well, those are just a few of my ideas. There are many tricks to slow enemies and make a castle easier to defend."
"Since you seem so sure of yourself, perhaps you won't want me around as long as I had hoped."
"We should get goin' again. Plenty more to do before we can start makin' changes to the keep."
"A barbican is an expanse of killin' ground, with a maze-like area to slow invaders who get inside the gates."
"A couple towers on either side would allow defenders to fire down into the kill zone and destroy many enemies."
"The barbican would be the most expensive, though they seem to have some good stoneworkers and masons here in the keep, judgin' by the defenses in place."
"The pits and stakes and a moat are less expensive, just labor intensive. There be enough people in this keep to do the job fairly quickly, if everyone able could help out."
"Thank you. That's really just a start. See, with a shortage of defenders, it is more important than ever to have a good assortment of artificial defenses."
Calibast smiles. "I am glad to hear that. I have had an idea. Maybe when you tire of rulin' this place, or when you have reached a pinnacle of power, maybe you could help me get revenge."
"In return for your help, I'll help you improve the keep and make it strong."
"The priestess was called Wren Bloodstone. I'll always remember that, because it seemed like such a gentle, sweet name. I was only there for a week before the first attack."
"I was only her general for a single war, but that was enough. I was more cautious than she had been in previous wars, which chafed at her a little. She wanted to attack the day after I arrived."
"Once I had all the information her scouts could provide, I marched my little army into the next town. I had planned strategies and followed my trainin', expectin' the worst."
He shrugs. "If that is the way you feel, I understand."
"It all proved to be unnecessary. Our army approached the town, and the elders came out to meet us. They were prepared to surrender without a fight. They wanted to join Wren's army."
"There was a slaughter, but not of my army. Our army approached the town, and the elders came out to meet us. They were prepared to surrender without a fight. They wanted to join Wren's army."
"I was overjoyed and Wren calmly accepted their surrender. She asked that all the people of the town come out and pay fealty to us."
"When all had presented themselves, she had them separated into groups. The men were asked to accompany a group of our soldiers to scour the outlyin' area for farmers and such."
Calibast looks very pale. "She was so calm and pleasant, even I didn't suspect anythin'. She spoke of how our combined forces would soon rule over the entire south."
"Once the men were gone, she had the women and elderly help build altars to Churl. Then she... I... I can't say the words. She had the men grab the villagers... they all died."
"It was not a story I shared. There are none who speak of it anymore."
"It was more madness than religion at that point. She had twisted the minds of her followers, leavin' only greed and malevolence and hate."
"At first I couldn't believe that she would do such a thing. She never informed me of what she had planned."
"When the work was finished she told the villagers to kneel and worship. As soon as they did, the slaughter started. It took the villagers and myself by surprise."
"By the time I recovered my wits, our army had killed all except the smallest children. Then it was my turn."
"Wren turned to me, laughin' and wild. She said 'You see the power of the goddess now?'"

"I never said another word. I drew my axe and I attacked her. It was a long and bloody battle, since she was very powerful and I had to fend off the soldiers at the same time, but in the end I removed her cursed head."
"Her death freed her followers from the spell that gripped their minds. They were so horrified by their actions, they surrendered immediately."
"I don't know how much of it was the spell and how much was greed, but with the death of their leader, they would have known their days were over."
"They deserved it. Some of them killed themselves in fits of horror, some ran off, some stayed to help the villagers rebuild, though I imagine they might have been killed by the returnin' villagers."
"Some of them killed themselves in fits of horror, some ran off, some stayed to help the villagers rebuild, though I imagine they might have been killed by the returnin' villagers."
"I didn't stay around. I left behind the blood money I had been paid and I traveled for many days. When I was far away, I found a tavern and drank myself into oblivion."
"Even now, the thought of the slaughter is enough to make me dizzy and nauseous. I drink to forget. I do anythin' to forget. Enough talk, for now."
"What a monstrous person. I can tell from your visage what happened."
"This story is beginning to make me feel sick with dread."
"I wasn't prepared for what happened, no. Our army approached the town, and the elders came out to meet us. They were prepared to surrender without a fight. They wanted to join Wren's army."
"You don't start with the easy topics, do you? I guess you never did. <StartAction>[Sigh]</Start> Let me think."
"My heavy drinkin' and carousin' started shortly after I came from my home plane to this one. I had suffered great tragedy and I wasn't ready for such a different life."
"I started life here as a mercenary. I had seen awful things in my life, but in my first year here in the south, I had never seen such utter barbarism."
"It was only a year before I met you, but the things I saw make it seem like it was an eternity."
"I arrived in a small village in the south, beyond the Withered Forest. The village was ruled by a dark priestess of Churl. I didn't know anythin' about the goddess of chaos, back then."
"You have already asked me one question. Let's stick to that subject for now. I'm not really in the mood to speak of my home right now."
"I arrived in a small village in the south, beyond the Withered Forest. The village was ruled by a dark priestess of Churl. I didn't know anythin' about the goddess of chaos, back then."
"The priestess of Churl hired me for my strength and she seemed to pay well enough. I thought I would just work for her long enough to get an understandin' of the way this world worked."
"She is the goddess of storms, destruction and chaos. The priestess who followed her took her role very seriously, tryin' to destroy all that surrounded her."
"She was very strong and had come to the village and destroyed the chief with lightnin' from the sky, then cast a spell that gave her control over the villager's minds."
"She had led the villagers to victory over the surroundin' villages and now they all had wealth and slaves. Greed and religious fanaticism can do strange things to a mind."
Calibast nods and chuckles. "Indeed, they will follow a fool, a wise man, a witch or a healer, given the right motivation."
"Improved their standard of livin', yes. Improved their lives, I think not."
"Where I come from, when a follower wants to get a message across to his leader, sometimes he will couch the advice in the form of a story. Listen and learn, oh mighty leader."
"They had just celebrated another victory when the sky ripped open and I fell out. They took it as another sign from the goddess."
"When they tried to grab me and drag me to the priestess, I threw them off. The priestess was impressed and after speakin' to me, offered me a position as her general."
"I accepted the role, for the reasons I already stated. The price was too great, but I would rather not speak about it right now. There is much to do. Let's be off."

Comment.value: if PC is on romance plot and Cal. has given up drinking.

value.0: "Of course, I would love to talk with you. What's on your mind, dear one?"
"We ready to go then?"
"We ready to go then?"
"You need to work on your people skills, <lad/lass>. Don't come to me unless you've come to your senses and want me back."
"It's about time. Let's go find somethin' to kill."
"If you can spare me a moment, I should like to speak with you."
"Of course you are. How foolish of me to think you could take the time to speak with your old leader. Mustn't forget who's in charge now, must we?"
"I don't find that particularly funny. Do I make fun of your penchant for openin' every chest, barrel and crate we come across? Do I?"
"How come you always think I be wantin' a drink? I do other things too... occasionally."
"Now, you can just stop that! You'd make fun of a friend just because he has a bit of a bad habit, would you?"
"Is it that obvious. Was it the shakes, or the red eyes that gave it away, huh?"
"Now that you mention it... ah, never mind. That's not what I wanted to talk about."
"What?" He roars. "That is slap in the face if I ever heard one... why, do you have some?"
--------- Random Conversations begin here ----------
"Can we talk about our situation here? I have several concerns knottin' up my gut. Either my liver has burst or I've got a bad case of nervous gas."
"We might not get a chance to talk later. Things are comin' to a head now."
"Very well then. Let's keep goin'."
"I just didn't want you to wonder if we were near the sewers or somethin'."

value.0: "I wanted to thank you for makin' me your Hand. I feel it as a badge of honor that I was worth your trust."
"I have crafted this ring for you. It contains some of my blood and energy. If I had been given the chance in life, I would have made one of these for the duke I served."
"It is a family tradition and it bonds me to you. So long as you want me around, and treat me with respect, I shall serve you with all of my ability."
"That is ridiculous! What is wrong with you? Very well, you have refused my bond. I shall remember this insult."
"It is more than friendship. I might be friends with someone who cheers me up, or who makes life interestin', yet not really respect them."
"You have my respect. You make me proud. Now, let us go forth and finish our enemy."
"You are welcome. You have made me proud, <FirstName>. Let us go forth and finish this enemy."
"I know that losin' the election must be pressin' hard on you, but I just want you to know that I still respect you. I think the keep lost out when they didn't choose you."
"You should have kept track of who had the most votes from Momma Dane and stolen the guilds from that person. If you took a few from both, you would have won."

value.0: "I have been thinkin' about the things you wanted me to change. You know, the stuff we discussed last time."

"Then we shall be stronger together... for so long as we have breath in our bodies. I need no ale, no wine, no other women, so long as I have you to intoxicate me."
"My life is yours to hold, keep or release, but know that I shall never be parted from you, so long as I can help it."

Comment.value: The PC knows about the King's betrayal

value.0: "But what we didn't realize was that Hastefel had the ear of our corrupt king. The king had always been jealous of the duke, for the duke was much loved by his people and his lands prospered."
"Maybe we were, but it seemed as though nothin' could go wrong with our plan. The war looked truly easy."
"We did, but the king claimed we had forged his letter of agreement. Hastefel was warned of the attack."
"We were besiegin' Hastefel's home castle when the king's troops arrived and attacked us from behind. We were declared traitors to the throne."
"Dash was devastated. He would never have betrayed his liege lord, the king. Caught between two armies, with our own troops demoralized, we surrendered."
"That was my opinion, too. My brother and Dash knew the battle was hopeless and they thought to save the men by surrenderin'. Dash figured a ransom would preserve his life."
"But that was not enough for the king. To gain the property of the duke, he decided that Dash would have to pay the traitor's price."
"None, and even that was not enough for the king. To gain the property of the duke, he decided that Dash would have to pay the traitor's price."
"Yes, but that was not enough for the king. To gain the property of the duke, he decided that Dash would have to pay the traitor's price."
"My brother, an accomplished warrior, declared himself Dash's champion. He challenged the king to send a champion and let the gods decide who was the traitor."

No... no... well.. sort of... but not in a one night stand sort of way."

Comment.value: set for after PC gains second vote

value.0: "Things are really startin' to come together. Two or three more votes and you'll be in position to win. But we had better not get cocky. I know what happens to the overconfident."
"No, we can speak of it later, I suppose. I wouldn't want to bother you when you're busy."
"My father trusted his sons implicitly. When I joined my brother's social group, I was pressured to tell everyone all about the new duke. They would hang on every word I said."
"Like a typical youth, I loved the attention. I told them exactly where Dash liked to hunt and when. A few weeks passed and my brother was treatin' me like an equal."
"Then Dash and I and father went huntin'. Several of the young courtiers volunteered to go huntin' with us, so we made a merry little huntin' party."
"I was only sixteen, but you are correct. My purpose was to protect the duke. That was my job."
"We were chasin' down a fire salamander the duke had wounded with an arrow. Suddenly there were a group of soldiers around us, come out of the obsidian forest."
"They were mercenary elementals and they attacked without hesitation. We would have died that day, if it were not for my father."
"He gave a mighty war cry and plunged into their weakest group. They went down easily and he cried to me to get the duke to safety."
"Of course I would. I would ask for no quarter from any enemy who attacked you. I would drive them off or die tryin'."
"I did as I was told. The duke and I had to kill a few of the elementals who came after us, but in the end we made it back to the castle."
"When we staggered into the main hall, the castle guards took the duke and rushed him to the healer. They were terribly shamed, even though they had been ordered to stay behind."
"I walked into the hall where my brother and his friends always drank and caroused. The look of shock on his face as he saw me... it was more a look of horror... it answered all of my questions."
"I watched as he tried to hide his shock behind a welcomin' smile. He opened his mouth and said somethin' about havin' a rough hunt, but I drew my axe and that shut him up."
"His friends were too stunned to try to stop me. I cleaved his traitorous head from his shoulders as I cried out that this was for our father."
"We... we need to get back to work now. I'll tell you more later, if you care to hear about it."
"Right. Sorry if I bothered you with my rant."
"You are a true friend, <FirstName>, and I thank you for listenin' to my rants."
"<FirstName>, I... um... do you think you could ever... ah... never mind!"

value.0: "Well, this is an interestin' turn of events, I would say. Not only have you taken over recent leadership of the party, but now you're movin' into high stakes leadership."
"Of course not. You're important now, at least in your own mind. No time to talk to an old friend."
"I suppose I do. I guess there is a little bit of bitterness in me, even though the thought of bein' a politician makes me shudder. But I am happy for you. I think you could be a very good leader."
"The two you are runnin' against, I'm thinkin' that they are very extreme. I worry about that, for the wars between such opposites can become very ugly."
"Don't be focusin' on Sir Becket and worryin' about him. Likewise, don't be trustin' Enivid too much. Don't forget, this is politics."
"That's the only attitude that can keep you alive. You can't afford to worry about what they are doin'. You have to concentrate on makin' these guildmasters want to vote for you."
"I'd be willin' to bet that Sir Becket is goin' to try somethin' slippery, like sendin' assassins after you. We will deal with them when the moment comes."
"Good. Don't make caution a fault though; you have a lot to accomplish in a short time. I guarantee, your opponents' supporters will push for a quick election as soon as you start gatherin' votes."
"Time is goin' to be precious. Keep that in mind. Now, I'm all finished with words, let's go find somethin' to kill!"
"No, aren't you payin' attention? Focus, <lad/lass>, focus. You take care of the election and concentrate on winnin'. I'll watch your back for you."
"You are goin' to have to trust me to watch your back. A good leader needs to know how to use the people around <him/her>."
"I'm not too bad with my weapon, in case you hadn't noticed. Any assassins come after you, I'll take care of them."
"I lived and breathed politics... growin' up. My father was the high council for a powerful duke. I and my brothers were groomed to take over for him. That's before the war though."
"I don't want to talk about that right now. I'll watch your back and make sure neither of the other candidates tries to stab it. You focus on winnin'."
"Of course this will be dangerous! Name one thing we've ever done that wasn't. But that's not the point. You have to ignore the danger and ignore your opponents."

value.0: "It occurs to me, with the recent change in our party leadership, that bein' from me to you, that we might want to examine the past few days before we go much further."
"Nah, I don't think that would be in our best interests. You always were a dominant personality; now you have the authority too."
Jaboli stares hard at him. "Are you sure you are feeling all right, old friend?"
"I think I made a mistake is all, and I just wanted you to know it. Do you want to talk about it or not?"
"That is fine, but don't be leavin' it for too long. I'll probably get drunk and forget what I wanted to say."
"I know you are the leader. As the leader you need to keep your mind open to suggestions from your followers, otherwise you'll just make the same mistakes I did."
"Very well. I know I was thick-headed too. I just thought you might prove a better leader than I did."
"I was given some advice when you began 'hearing' the rumors about the Masked Man. Some in our group thought that we should take some time to truly assess our enemy before we started huntin' him."
"Truthfully, they all did. And it turns out they were right to be skeptical."
"You were like a <man/woman> possessed. You could describe him in detail, chart his every move upon your map. I should have been more suspicious."
"All I cared about was catchin' him, maybe shakin' him down for treasure. I figured we could tackle one man in a mask and his paltry army. But not everyone saw it that way."
"Trip, of course, was terrified at even the thought of facin' such a figure. I wouldn't listen to a word. I had made up my mind and I agreed with you."
"I should have listened to the others. As leader it was my job to exercise caution. Now it is yours. We are dependin' on you."
"I don't know if you are bein' serious, or sarcastic, but I hope you listen to my advice."
"Not at all. I should have listened to the others. As leader it was my job to exercise caution. Now it is yours. We are dependin' on you."
"I think we need to be careful. There is a mystery here, and your weapon is all wrapped up in it."
"Just don't be afraid to ask for help. That's how we might just survive these perilous times. That and with a bit of luck."
"As the leader you need to keep your mind open to suggestions from your followers, otherwise you'll just make the same mistakes I did."
"Ack, there's nothin' to bring a person down more than a bloody, awful death! I'll try to do better and not die on you again. No promises though! You ready to go?"
"Blast it! I said I'd try not to die again. What more can you ask a man?"
"Good, and <FirstName>? Try not to give me any orders that lead me straight into Mistress Death's realm, right-oh? Here we go."
"Just stay away from me, you ripe fool! I've nothin' to say to you."
"What I would nae give for a strong draft of ale right now."
"Jaboli, do you remember that time when you fell off that castle wall and landed in the moat?"
She glares at Calibast. "I seem to recall that someone was supposed to be holding the rope!"
"I didn't think you'd actually let go of the wall, but that's not what I wanted to talk about. When you landed in the water, I was shocked."
"I don't have a head that is constantly on fire. A little water doesn't bother me."
"Oh, a little dousin' won't put out my flames, let me reassure you of that. But that is not what I meant."
"Oh, I get it. This is another 'cat' topic. Cats usually hate water, so I too should hate water. As I have said a thousand times before, I am not a cat! I enjoy swimming."
"You really are a disagreeable woman! That's not what I meant either."
"My apologies. I should not jump to conclusions. Please, what were you going to say?"
"Just that when you came out of the water, your robe was very... clingy. I was shocked at how nice your... physique was."
"And if anyone would notice a fine female body, it would be you."
"Exactly. I just wanted you to know that you really are quite attractive... for a cat." Calibast starts laughing uncontrollably.
Jaboli rolls her eyes. "Men!"
"I was just wonderin', Jaboli, do you hate dogs?"
"I have neither a great fondness for them, nor an abnormal hatred or fear of them. Why do you ask?"
"I should think that it would be obvious. I mean, I guess there are a few cats and dogs that get along, but on the whole they tend to feud for the most part."
"What is it with you people that you seem to think that just because I have similar... features to a cat, that it means I really am a cat?"
"It could be that when you get mad you kind of make a hissin' noise and when you are happy... well, you purr."
Jaboli stares daggers at Calibast.
"Well, I was just goin' to say that I like cats. Not everybody does, you know. I knew a guy once who would go out of his way to get within kickin' distance of a cat. I'm not that way."
"Obviously you are cut of a finer cloth than your friend. Not fine enough to recognize the difference between a cat and a rakshasa, sadly."
"You don't have to take offense. I was just wantin' you to know that I thought you are a fine-lookin' female, for a cat."
"I always thought you were such a smooth talker, Calibast. But such a clumsy attempt to flirt with me tells me you must be losing your touch."
"You've been dyin' for a chance to say that, haven't you?"
Jaboli just hisses at the two of you and turns away.
"I was tryin' to get along. That was why I was tryin' to compliment her. But no... she's got to get all catty on me."
"How long have you been saving that one?"
"Several days, but it was worth it." He winks at her.
Jaboli just hisses at him and turns away.
"I'm hurt. I was just tryin' to give her a compliment. But no... she's got to get all catty on me.""

value.0: "What?"
He winks at you, then leers at Kaidala again. "Come on, lass. You're a nymph, or at least you used to be. Have you forgotten your roots?"
"Of course I haven't forgotten my roots!"
"What a sweet girl you are!" They both look at your face and then start to laugh.
"Sorry, <FirstName>. We were just having a little fun with you."
"Hoo! You should have seen your face. Now that's what I call fun!"
"How long have we been adventurin' together, Kaidala? Why do you stare at me with that look of horror still?"
"I am sorry, Calibast. I don't mean to offend you. It is just the constant flames on your head... they live in my mind, still burning my own face."
"But fire is beautiful. Yes, it is also destructive and dangerous, but without it, most would not survive."
"Nature keeps me warm, even in the depths of winter. I eat fruit and vegetables and nuts, so I have no need to cook food with it. Fire holds no gifts for me."
"Fire allows us to make weapons and armor. Fire provides light. Even you could not survive without the sun!"
"The sun... yes, it is true that my kind need the sun. And when part of a forest burns, what is left behind fertilizes the area and helps new plants grow. I am wary of fire, but I do not hate it."
"So it is specific to the fact that my head is burnin'?"
"It is. Yes."
"In all the time we have been together, you have never touched my head."
"I... I don't think I could do that."
"Come, just lay your hand on my cheek. I promise I won't hurt you."
She hesitantly reaches out. "Oh... um... it's cool... like touching regular flesh."
"You are. The flames are controllable, so I can cool them for others, but they never hurt me. My entire body is immune to the touches of fire."
"I guess that might help, a little. It still doesn't stop my memories."
"I know, but hopefully now you can look at me without that look of total repugnance. Actually, the touch of your hand is very gentle. A lot can be said in a single touch."
"Oh, sorry about that. Old habits die hard, I suppose."
"Trip, I fear I have done you a disservice, lad. My guilty conscience must be purged."
"Trip is not sure what you are talking about, Calibast. What is this conscience thing you speak of?"
"Mmm, well, not important. Not surprised you don't really know, but that's not what I wanted to tell you."
"That makes no sense to Trip, but go ahead."
"I have to admit that I once saw a wookalar. It was very much alive and more fearsome than anythin' I had ever seen, or have seen since."
"Then there is another one? There really is? Oh, joy! Trip was right!"
"Yes, but the reason that I didn't want to talk about it, is that the... um... creature is drawn to people that talk about it."
"Really? But Trip has talked about it many times before and yet never seen one." Trip's whiskers start to tremble.
"You have!? How many times have you said the name?" Calibast begins to look frantically.
"Trip is not so sure. Maybe fifty times." Trip starts to look very nervous.
"Fifty?" Calibast whistles. "That's just about how many times my brother talked about it when the creature came out of the shadows for him!"
Trip starts glancing about nervously. "You lost your brother to a wookalar?"
"You said it again! What are you tryin' to do, get us all killed?"
"Sorry! Trip is sorry! I did not mean to say it again."
"Wait! Shh. What was that? Did you hear it, <FirstName>?"
"Oh no, eek!"
"It's over there, behind you, Trip!"
"Well, that was fun."
"Ack, you are too soft on the lad! It was only a joke."
"You would joke about such a thing? That is so cruel, Calibast! Trip is ashamed of your actions. How could you be so mean?"
Calibast looks a little guilty. "Oh, fine, I'm sorry. Now, forget about it and lets go do some more killin'!"
"Watch where you're goin', you flea-infested, giant mouse."
"What did Trip do now? Why you always got to be so mean to me?"
"You bloody-well almost tripped me, that's what you did! I suppose you got your name from the number of people you've tripped in your life?"
"Oh, no. Trip is named after the smallest hero ever who also happened to destroy the worst monster ever."
"You're full of lies and deceit. I have never heard of a hero named Trip."
"Sorry, <master/mistress>. Trip only tries to answer big flame-head."
"I was just askin' ratman a question. No need to get touchy."
"Trip is telling the truth! There was a little half-fellow named Tripcanticius who defeated the most dreadful monster in the world... the horrible wookalar!"
"There is no such thing as a wookalar! That's only a myth."
"No such beast now, but when the first Trip was alive, the wookalar was the most dangerous of all the monsters in the land."
"And you think I'm supposed to believe in this creature that had tusks, a pig's snout, and long, sharp nails that could reach up through your nose and pull out your brains?"
"Wow, you know lots about the wookalar. Have you met a wookalar? Maybe your home has wookalars?"
"THERE IS NO SUCH THING AS A WOOKALAR! It isn't real! It's a myth! Get it through your head! I just made that tripe up!"
"But then how come you just described one perfectly?"
"Just... get... away... from... me." He fumes and stomps his feet in aggravation.
"Not yet. I will come back for you."
"Yes. Please follow me."
"Never mind."
"I think we need to part ways."
"No, never mind."
"Wait here until I return."
"I need to go."
